-- 
Singapore Stocks: CapitaLand, Noble, Portek, Singapore Press

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-07-13T04:55:10Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-13/noble-group-portek-singapore-press-singapore-equity-preview.html
Singapore ’s  Straits Times Index (FSSTI) 
gained 0.3 percent to 3,087.51 as of the 12:30 p.m. trading
break. Almost two stocks rose for each that fell in the gauge of
30 companies.  Shares on the measure trade at an average 14.2 times
estimated earnings, compared with about 15.6 times at the end of
2010, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  Developers in  China : Homebuilders in China advanced after
the nation’s economic growth rate slowed in the second quarter,
which may ease inflation pressures. Demand is holding up in the
fastest-growing major economy even after the central bank
boosted lending rates five times since mid-October and raised
bank reserve requirements to a record.  CapitaLand Ltd. (CAPL)  , Southeast Asia’s biggest
developer that gets about 21 percent of its sales from China,
climbed 3.1 percent to S$2.97.  Yanlord Land Group Ltd. (YLLG)  ,
a Chinese homebuilder, increased 1.7 percent to S$1.205.
 Guocoland Ltd. (GUOL)  , a real-estate company that counts
China as its biggest market, added 0.9 percent to S$2.16.  Noble Group Ltd. (NOBL)  , a Hong Kong-based supplier of
commodities, gained 0.3 percent to S$1.88. The company said it
will receive $3.2 billion of revolving credit facilities from
banks including Citigroup Inc. and DBS Group Holdings Ltd.  Portek International Ltd. (PORT)  , the operator of port
facilities in Indonesia, Algeria, Malta and Gabon, surged 6.1
percent to S$1.40 before trading was halted. The company said it
received a takeover offer from Mitsui & Co. The Japanese trading
company plans to offer S$1.40 per Portek share, it said. That
exceeds the S$1.20 per share bid by International Container
Terminal Services Inc. of the Philippines.  Singapore Technologies Engineering Ltd. (STE)  , Asia’s
biggest aircraft maintenance company, rose 0.7 percent to S$2.98.
The company said its ST Kinetics unit won a contract to supply
buses to SMRT Corp. (MRT SP), operator of commuter trains,
public buses and taxis in Singapore.  Singapore Press Holdings Ltd. (SPH)  , the city-state’s
biggest newspaper publisher, lost 0.5 percent to S$3.89. The
company said third-quarter net income fell 30 percent to S$114.8
million ($93.4 million) from a year earlier after it didn’t
repeat a gain from the sale of a housing project.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in Singapore at 
